<HEAD>For Release Friday, Sept. 15</HEAD>
<HEAD>Today In History</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Today is Friday, Sept. 15, the 258th day of 1989. There are 107
days left in the year.
   Today's highlight in history:
   One hundred years ago, on Sept. 15, 1889, humorist, critic and
actor Robert Benchley was born in Worcester, Mass.
   On this date:
   In 1776, British forces occupied New York City during the
American Revolution.
   In 1789, 200 years ago, the U.S. Department of Foreign Affairs
was renamed the Department of State.
   In 1821, independence was proclaimed for Costa Rica, Guatemala,
Honduras, Nicaragua and El Salvador.
   In 1857, William Howard Taft _ who served as president of the
United States as well as chief justice _ was born in Cincinnati.
   In 1887, Philadelphia launched a three-day celebration of the
100th anniversary of the Constitution of the United States.
   In 1917, Russia was proclaimed a republic by Alexander Kerensky,
the head of the provisional government that came to power following
the abdication of Czar Nicholas II.
   In 1935, the Nuremberg Laws deprived German Jews of their
citizenship and made the swastika the official symbol of Nazi
Germany.
   In 1940, during the Battle of Britain in World War II, the tide
turned as Royal Air Force planes inflicted heavy losses against the
Luftwaffe.
   In 1949, ``The Lone Ranger,'' based on the radio show of the same
name, made its television debut on ABC with Clayton Moore as the
masked hero and Jay Silverheels as Tonto.
   In 1950, during the Korean conflict, United Nations forces landed
at Inchon in the south and began their drive toward Seoul.
   In 1959, Soviet Premier Nikita S. Khrushchev arrived in the
United States to begin a 13-day visit.
   In 1963, four children were killed when a bomb went off during
Sunday services at a black Baptist church in Birmingham, Ala.
   In 1969, Steve Carlton of the St. Louis Cardinals struck out 19
New York Mets. Carlton's strikeout record was broken by Roger
Clemens with 20 in 1986.
   In 1978, Muhammad Ali won a unanimous, 15-round decision over
World Boxing Association heavyweight champion Leon Spinks at the
Louisiana Superdome in New Orleans.
   In 1982, Israeli forces began pouring into west Beirut following
the assassination of Lebanese President-elect Bashir Gemayel.
   In 1982, Iran's former foreign minister, Sadegh Ghotbzadeh, was
executed after he was convicted of plotting against the government.
   In 1983, the Senate joined the House of Representatives in
approving a resolution condemning the Soviet Union for shooting down
a Korean jetliner with 269 aboard.
   Ten years ago: The Chrysler Corporation asked for $1.2 billion
dollars in federal loan guarantees, but was turned down by the
Carter administration.
   Five years ago: Sharlene Wells of Utah was crowned Miss America
1985 in Atlantic City, N.J., succeeding Suzette Charles, who had
replaced Vanessa Williams as Miss America 1984 because of the
Penthouse scandal that forced Williams' resignation.
   One year ago: Thousands of coastal residents from Mexico to
Louisiana were fleeing to higher ground, a day after Hurricane
Gilbert pounded the Yucatan Peninsula.
   Today's birthdays: Country music star Roy Acuff is 86.
Actor-director Jackie Cooper is 67. Comedian Norm Crosby is 62.
Former baseball player Gaylord Perry is 51. Actor-sportscaster
Merlin Olsen is 49. Actor Tommy Lee Jones is 43. Football
quarterback Dan Marino is 28. Britain's Prince Henry of Wales is 5.
   Thought for today: ``For a nation which has an almost evil
reputation for bustle, bustle, bustle, and rush, rush, rush, we
spend an enormous amount of time standing around in line in front of
windows, just waiting.'' _ Robert Benchley, U.S. humorist
(1889-1945).
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Advance for Friday, Sept. 15</NOTE>
